{"key":"processedPost-9436172","value":{"id":9436172,"first":9435304,"last":9436329,"when":1229366349,"utime":"12/15/08 08:39 PM","content":"The q-tip test is bogus, because small pieces of bruised mycelium can rub off on the q-tip making the inexperienced eye think it's mold.<br /><br />Bruising is bruising.&nbsp; The analogy of bruising on your body carries over to mushrooms.&nbsp; A bruised fruit or cake will have a blue or green color, but it's the <i>color of the tissue</i>.&nbsp;  If it's mold, it will look more like a scab from a wound on your body.&nbsp; Mold spores will be on the <b>surface as a separate layer</b>, just like a scab on your arm.&nbsp; Another analogy is that mold spores often look like a layer of green sand on the surface of the fruit.<br />RR","title":"Re: little bit of green on one side and some pins on the other","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}